   169
   170	Use `ios-e2e-runner` to validate and run generalized multi-peer iOS UI E2E sessions. The runner config is project-neutral: product repositories provide peer mappings, Xcode destinations, selectors, and scenario event names in their own config or test code.
   171
   172	The full config contract, reserved environment keys, and artifact layout are documented in [.spec/e2e-coordinator-config-schema.md](.spec/e2e-coordinator-config-schema.md).
   173
   174	Keep product-specific examples in the consumer project that owns the workflow. Toolkit docs should use neutral peer names, event names, bundle placeholders, and device placeholders.
   175
   176	Dry-run validates the config and prints the exact peer launch plan without building, installing, launching devices, or starting UI tests:
   177
   178	```bash
   179	DEVELOPER_DIR=/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer \
   180	swift run ios-e2e-runner \
   181	  --config Samples/IOSE2ECoordinator/dry-run-two-peer.yaml \
   182	  --dry-run \
   183	  --session-id sample-session
   184	```
   185
   186	To run a real coordinator session, use the same config shape without `--dry-run`. The config must point at reachable physical devices or simulators, valid Xcode projects, and UI test selectors owned by the consumer project:
   187
   188	```bash
   189	DEVELOPER_DIR=/Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer \
   190	swift run ios-e2e-runner \
   191	  --config path/to/e2e-physical.yaml \
   192	  --session-id physical-validation-001 \
   193	  --developer-dir /Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer
   194	```
   195
   196	The runner injects reserved `E2E_*` environment values into every peer process so UI tests can connect to the coordinator through `IOSE2EPeerClient`.
   197
   198	UI test targets that participate in a coordinator session should import `IOSE2EPeerClient` and create the peer client from the injected environment:
   199
   200	```swift
   201	import IOSE2EPeerClient
   202	import XCTest
   203
   204	final class PeerScenarioTests: XCTestCase {
   205	    func testScenario() async throws {
   206	        let client = try await UITestE2EClient.fromEnvironment()
   207	        defer { client.close() }
   208
   209	        if client.environment.peerNameValue == "peer-a" {
   210	            try await client.publish("peer-a.ready", delivery: .acked())
   211	            _ = try await client.waitFor("peer-b.ready", timeout: 30)
   212	        } else {
   213	            _ = try await client.waitFor("peer-a.ready", timeout: 30)
   214	            try await client.publish("peer-b.ready", delivery: .acked())
   215	        }
   216	    }
   217	}
   218	```
   219
   220	Physical devices must be able to open TCP connections to the coordinator host. When all peers share the same LAN route, set `coordinator.advertisedHost` once. When peers need different routes to the same coordinator, for example separate wired or lab-network interfaces, set `coordinatorHost` on the individual peer; the runner keeps the global coordinator bind/port/path and injects a peer-specific `E2E_COORDINATOR_URL`.
   221
